survivoR project

Carrie Snodgrass and Lilly Nikkel

Abstract

We run statistical analysis on factors that influence the performance of contestants on the reality TV show Survivor. We visualize different predictors and run multiple-regression analysis. Factors include a contestants age, votes cast against the contestant, the number of challenges won, and personality type. We determined statistical significant predictors include number of challenges (immunity idols) won and the second of the four Meyers-Brigss personality traits, which is whether a contestant is more intuitive or more sensing.

Introduction

Survivor is one of the longest-running reality TV shows, premiering in 2000 with 42 seasons up to date. The basic premise of the game is that, in each episode, the contestants, or castaways vote to eliminate one player, and the last castaway remaining is the winner. We found a data set with data from the 1st through 40th seasons. The data set is focused on the castaways, with information based on their person hoods, such as age and hometown, and information based on their performance, such as where they placed and how many votes they received throughout the game. We want to determine what factors have the greatest effect, if any, on how well a castaway performs during the show

Exploratory Data Analysis

The data set we used has most basic relevant data. We wish there were some other basic data included, like contestant gender, or hidden immunity idols. The data set also included qualitative data irrelevant to our analysis, such as tribe name and tribes switched.

A Regression of Order Voted on Immunity Idols Won (from challenges)

Each day in the season, contestants compete in a challenge; the winner of a any challenge gets an immunity idol which gives them immunity from being voted off for that day.

The order refers to the order in which contestants were voted off; a higher order number means that the contestant survived longer.

We used geom_jitter so that we could accurately see the distribution of contestants who won each number of immunity idols, since both the number of immunity idols and the order voted off are discrete variables.

This graph clearly sugggests that winning more immunity idols is associated with staying on the show longer.

Regresssion of Total Votes Received on Immunity Idols Won

Total Votes Received is the total number of votes cast against a player throughout the season.

We plotted immunity idols won against total votes received (and plotted a regression line) to see if immunity idols won had any impact on how other contestants viewed that player (demonstrated by whether or not they were voted for in other rounds)

We used geom_jitter here again so that we could accurately see the distribution of contestants who won each number of immunity idols and who received each number of votes, since both the number of immunity idols and the number of votes received are discrete variables.

The graph suggests that there may be weak negative correlation between the two variables, if any at all.

Distribution of Personality Types

Our data set included the Meyers-Briggs personality type of each contestant.The Meyers-Briggs Personality Test assigns a personality type based on four traits: extraversion vs introversion; sensing vs intuition; thinking vs feeling; and judging vs perceiving. It should be noted that the methodologies for how the contestants were typed is unknown. We proceed with caution.

This bar graph visualizes the distribution of personality types represented by all of the contestants.

A Regression of Order On Age

We plotted order against age (and plotted a regression line) to see if a contestants age (at the time of competition) had any impact on how long a contestant lasted on the show.

We used geom_jitter here again so that we could accurately see the distribution of the elimination order of contestants at each age, since both age and order are discrete variables.

The graph suggests that there may be weak negative correlation between the two variables, if any at all.

Plotting Viewership by Season

We also have data on viewership for each season; we plotted mean viewership by season, and we can see a clear descending trend. We chose not to pursue working with this data.

Statistical Analysis

Hypothesis Testing for Regression Coefficients (Order on Immunity Idols Won)

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = order ~ immunity_idols_won, data = castaways)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -15.822  -3.505  -0.420   3.495  11.495 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                    Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)          8.5054     0.1973   43.11   <2e-16 ***
## immunity_idols_won   2.8291     0.1832   15.44   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.798 on 742 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2432, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2422 
## F-statistic: 238.5 on 1 and 742 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
## [1] 0.4931756

In this hypothesis test, we are investigating whether winning immunity idols has an effect on the order a contestant is voted off. We start with the equation

orderi = b0 + b1immunity_idols_won.

We perform a hypothesis test based on the regressions visualized in the section entitled A Regression of Order Voted on Immunity Idols Won (from challenges).

Therefore, our null hypothesis is that the number of immunity idols won has no effect on the order a contestant is voted off (H0: b1 = 0), Our alternative hypothesis is that the number of immunity idols won does have an effect on the order a player is voted off (Ha: b1 0).

The p-value for this test is less than .01, so we can reject the null hypothesis (that immunity idols won has no effect on order) at any standard level of confidence.

This makes sense, because winning an immunity idol means that the contestant will automatically stay an additional day.

It is interesting to note that the estimated coefficient on immunity idols is 2.8, which suggests that each additional immunity idol won is associated with an additional 2.8 days on the show.

The multiple R2 is .24, which means that 24.32% of the variation in order can be explained by our model.

The correlation between immunity idols won and order is .493.

## Multiple R-squared:  0.003215,   Adjusted R-squared:  -0.002202 
## F-statistic: 0.5935 on 4 and 736 DF,  p-value: 0.6674

We separated the 4 personality traits of the Meyers-Briggs Personality types into individual dummy variables and ran a regression using just those so we could investigate how each pair of traits affects a contestants performance.

orderi = b0 + b1extraversioni + b2intuitivei + b3thinkingi +b4judgingi

Therefore, our null hypothesis is that each of the personality traits has no effect on the order a contestant is voted off (H0: bi = 0 for all i), Our alternative hypothesis is that one or more personality traits has an effect on the order a player is voted off (Ha: bi 0 for at least 1 i.).

The coefficients on each of the variables can be found in the table.

The p-value for the coefficient on extraversion vs introversion is 0.592. The p-value for the coefficient on intuitive vs sensing is 0.208. The p-value for the coefficient on thinking vs feeling is .835. The p-value for the coefficient on judging vs perceiving is .446.

The p-values for each coefficient are greater than .05, so we fail to reject our null hypothesis that each of the personality traits has no effect on order voted off.

The multiple R2 is .003, which means that .003% of the variation in order can be explained by our model.

This test suggests that the Meyers Briggs personality traits do not have much of an effect on how well contestants do in Survivor.

We performed a multiple-regression of order on age, immunity idols won, total votes received, and each of the 4 Meyers-Briggs personality traits as 4 separate dummy variables.

The only variables with statistically significant results were immunity idols won, and intuitive vs sensing, which have p-values of less than 2e-16 and .0602 for each of the coefficients respectively.

This is notable because in our regression with just the personality traits, the p-value was not statistically significant for intuitive or sensing.

As some more context on sensing vs intuition, those who are more sensing pay more attention to information that comes through the five senses. Those who are more intuitive pay more attention to the patterns and possibilities that they see.

We performed another regression on order using just immunity idols won and intuitive vs sensing, as those were the only two regressors with statistically significant p-values.

We noticed that the p-value on intuitive is slightly lower in this regression than in the previous regression; this suggests that intuitive vs sensing is not independent of at least some of the other regressors.

The multiple R2 for this test is 0.248, which suggests that 24.8% of the variation in order can be explained by our model. This is only a .48% difference from the R2 in our regression using only immunity idols as a regressor. This suggests that intuitive has a small effect on the order by which a contestant is voted off, but a very small impact.

Conclusion

We have evidence to suggest that winning immunity idols is likely to help contestants stay on the show longer. We also have evidence to suggest that intuition is statistically significant predictor of contestants order (although the affect appears to be very small).

Our analysis suggests that the other factors we examined, including age, total votes received, and the other personality traits have no effect on the order a contestant is voted off.
